definition.value: An oral contraceptive containing only the hormone progestogen.
Contraceptive pills that contain only synthetic progestogens (progestins) and do not contain estrogen. They are colloquially known as mini pills.
A contraceptive administered via the surface of the skin, with minimal penetration of the skin layer.
A drug prescribed for gynecological use; that is, for an affected area or areas studied primarily in gynecology.
A contraceptive which is placed inside the uterus.
A contraceptive which is placed inside the vagina.
A contraceptive administered via the surface of the skin, with maximum penetration of the skin layer in efforts to exert effects on deeper tissues.
A device used for the purposes of hormonal contraception.

A polymeric drug delivery device designed to provide controlled release of drugs for intravaginal administration over extended periods of time. The ring is inserted into the vagina and provides contraceptive protection.
Consent to engage in sexual activity.
A branch of medicine dealing with the use of surgery to treat diseases of the breast.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the limbs.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of lower extremities.
Surgery in which the lower extremity is repaired.

The plastic surgery and the liposuction procedures for the correction of the congenital, traumatic, and acquired defects and deformities of the buttocks and the anatomy of the gluteal region; and for the aesthetic enhancement (by augmentation or by reduction) of the contour of the buttocks.
The use of operant conditioning, including rewards and punishments, in assist a person in creating an atmosphere where he or she does not contribute to "painful" stimuli.
Alteration or modification of an aspect of one's or one's entire sexual orientation identity.
Alteration or modification of an aspect of one's or one's entire gender identity.
The pseudoscientific practice of trying to change an individual's sexual orientation from gay to straight/heterosexual using psychological and/or spiritual interventions.
The pseudoscientific practice of trying to change an individual's gender identity using psychological and/or spiritual interventions; any of various attempts to "make" someone cisgender.
The pseudoscientific practice of trying to change an individual's sexual orientation or gender identity using psychological and/or spiritual interventions.
Alteration or modification of an aspect of one's or one's entire identity.
An intersectional theory that draws from queer theory and which considers disability as an essential part of identity,
The adoption of elements of one culture by members of another culture. This can be controversial when members of a dominant culture appropriate from disadvantaged minority cultures.
A personal name entered onto a legal document, typically a birth register or birth certificate, around the period of one's birth. This name becomes that person's legal name at that point.
A name that identifies a person for legal, administrative and other official purposes.

It should be noted that, in many jurisdictions, there is no such concept as a "legal name". Oftentimes such a construct, rather than being related to any aspect of law or medical care, is used as an excuse to deadname and misgender transgender persons.
The augmentation of the buttock, typically utilizing a gluteal implant under each gluteus maximus muscle; lipoinjection; or by rearranging and enhancing muscle and fat tissues of the gluteal region.
To assign to someone a particular identity, usually based on visual appearances.
Process in which gender is assigned or attributed to an individual without asking that person their gender identity.
Any of various romantic orientations falling on the aromantic spectrum between alloromantic and aromantic.
Romantically attracted to people only after forming deep emotional bonds.
The process of changing one's gender presentation and/or sex characteristics to accord with one's internal sense of gender identity.

Transitioning is an umbrella term for changes undertaken to match their gender expression with their identified gender. Typically, there are two forms of gender transition: social transition (wearing different clothing, speaking with a difference cadence, using a diferent name, etc.) and physical transition (usage of hormones, various gender-affirming surgeries, etc.). Usually this distinction is unnecessary and used as a form of gatekeeping.
Cessation of gender transition for any reason.

There are many reasons for detransitioning, including one's personal safety, health concerns unrelated to being transgender, regaining of fertility, stigma related to being transgender, the costs associated with transgender medical transition, and/or the stigma associated with being transgender.
Transitioning after stopping gender transition for any reason.
Cessation of a particular behavior or behaviors.

Desistance from a gender identity considered transgender; i.e. a person assigned female at birth who formerly identified as male identifies as female. More broadly, any desistance of a particular gender identity.

Desistance from a sexual orientation identity which is nonheterosexual in nature; i.e. a person who formerly identified as gay identifies as heterosexual. More broadly, any desistance from any sexual orientation including heterosexuality.
A covering designed to be worn on the body.
Fabric or other material used to cover the body. Distinctive apparel worn by members of an organization.
Clothing (such as a dress) worn over one's underwear.
Clothing worn over one's undergarments, typically or primarily indoors.
Clothing (such as a rain jacket) worn over one's clothes, to protect them (e.g. against rain) when outside.

A garment consisting of a skirt with an attached bodice (or a matching bodice giving the effect of a one-piece garment). It consists of a top piece that covers the torso and hangs down over the legs. A dress can be any one-piece garment containing a skirt of any length and can be formal or casual.
Collective human activities involved in the production of goods and services; or the physical or mental exertion of individuals to produce or accomplish something.
The process of managing feelings and expressions to fulfill the emotional requirements of a job.
Removal of all traces of something; obliteration.

A heteronormative cultural practice where queer people are erased from cultural narratives. Queer erasure (inclusive of lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and asexual erasure) is used in both scholarly and popular media texts when referring to issues of visibility and exclusion, such as in the case of AIDS research that does not include lesbian populations.
A cultural practice where asexual people are erased from cultural narratives.

the tendency to ignore, remove, falsify, or reexplain evidence of bisexuality in history, academia, the news media, and other primary sources. In its most extreme form, bisexual erasure can include the belief that bisexuality does not exist.
A cultural practice where gay people, particular gay men, are erased from cultural narratives.
A cultural practice where intersex people are erased from cultural narratives.
A cultural practice where transgender people are erased from cultural narratives. Transgender persons may also be ignored within the LGBTQIA+ community and their identity may not be acknowledged.
